10 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
11 An Act relating to the Oklahoma Firefighters Pension
and Retirement System; amending 11 O.S. 2021,
12 Sections 49-101 and 49-101.2, as amended by Sections
3 and 4, Chapter 232, O.S.L. 2022 (11 O.S. Supp.
13 2025, Sections 49-101 and 49-101.2), which relate to
volunteer firefighter pensions; modifying pension
14 amount; modifying compensation determination;
authorizing benefit increase for certain retired
15 members of the Oklahoma Firefighters Pension and
Retirement System; amending 62 O.S. 2021, Section
16 3103, as last amended by Section 2, Chapter 361,
O.S.L. 2024 (62 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 3103), which
17 relates to the Oklahoma Pension Legislation Actuarial
Analysis Act; modifying certain definition; updating
18 statutory language; providing for codification; and
providing effective dates.
19
20
21 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
22 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 11 O.S. 2021, Section 49-101, as
23 amended by Section 3, Chapter 232, O.S.L. 2022 (11 O.S. Supp. 2025,
24 Section 49-101), is amended to read as follows:
Req. No. 3872 Page 1

RBS No. 3872
1 Section 49-101. A. All retired volunteer firefighters who
2 qualify for retirement shall be entitled to a monthly pension. The
3 monthly pension of a volunteer firefighter who retires prior to the
4 effective date of this section shall be in the amount retired
5 volunteer firefighters are receiving at the time the volunteer
6 firefighter begins to receive a pension for each year of credited
7 service not to exceed thirty (30) years. Volunteer firefighters who
8 retire on and after the effective date of this section shall receive
9 a monthly pension in the amount of Ten Dollars ($10.00) for each
10 year of credited service not to exceed thirty (30) years. In
11 determining the number of years of credited service, a fractional
12 year of six (6) months or more shall be counted as one (1) full year
13 and a fractional year of less than six (6) months shall not be
14 counted in such determination. Retired volunteer firefighters of a
15 municipality shall receive a pension of not less than that which
16 retired volunteer firefighters of such municipality were receiving
17 on June 30, 1985.
18 B. A volunteer firefighter who terminates service after
19 completing ten (10) years of credited service, but less than twenty
20 (20) years of credited service, shall be entitled to receive a
21 vested benefit commencing on the date the firefighter reaches fifty
22 (50) years of age or the date the firefighter would have had twenty
23 (20) years of credited service had the firefighter’s service
24 continued uninterrupted, whichever is later. The monthly amount of
Req. No. 3872 Page 2

RBS No. 3872
1 such retirement benefit shall be the amount being paid to volunteer
2 firefighters at the time the member vests multiplied by the number
3 of years of credited service. Credited service must be established
4 at the time of the volunteer firefighter’s termination. If a
5 volunteer firefighter who terminated employment and elected, or was
6 eligible to elect, a vested benefit dies prior to being eligible to
7 receive benefits, the volunteer firefighter’s beneficiary, as
8 defined in paragraph 16 of Section 49-100.1 of this title, shall be
9 entitled to the volunteer firefighter’s normal monthly retirement
10 benefit on the date the deceased volunteer firefighter would have
11 been eligible to receive the benefit.
12 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 11 O.S. 2021, Section 49-101.2, as
13 amended by Section 4, Chapter 232, O.S.L. 2022 (11 O.S. Supp. 2025,
14 Section 49-101.2), is amended to read as follows:
15 Section 49-101.2. Any member serving as an active volunteer
16 firefighter who receives annual compensation from the fire
17 department the firefighter is enrolled in as a member of the
18 Oklahoma Firefighters Pension and Retirement System for services
19 related to firefighting, other than reimbursement of expenses in
20 excess of five and one-half (5 1/2) times the annual pension benefit
21 paid by the System to a retired volunteer firefighter with twenty
22 (20) years credited service Nine Thousand Nine Hundred Thirty-nine
23 Dollars and sixty-nine cents ($9,939.69), shall be considered a paid
24 firefighter and must meet the physical and agility requirements
Req. No. 3872 Page 3

RBS No. 3872
1 purs uant to Section 49-116 of this title to continue as an active
2 member of the System. Credited service earned as a paid firefighter
3 pursuant to this section shall not be considered actual experience
4 as a paid firefighter for purposes of meeting the qualifications of
5 a paid fire chief as provided in Section 29-102 of this title. No
6 fire department of a participating municipality shall employ a
7 volunteer firefighter from another fire department to perform
8 services relating to firefighting for any compensation of any kind.
9 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
10 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 49-143.8 of Title 11, unless
11 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
12 A. Except as provided in subsection B of this section, any
13 person receiving benefits from the Oklahoma Firefighters Pension and
14 Retirement System as of June 30, 2026, who continues to receive
15 benefits on or after the effective date of this section, shall
16 receive an increase in benefits as follows:
17 1. Zero percent (0%) if the person has been retired for less
18 than ten (10) years as of June 30, 2026;
19 2. Three percent (3%) if the person has been retired for at
20 least ten (10) years but less than twenty (20) years as of June 30,
21 2026; and
22 3. Six percent (6%) if the person has been retired for twenty
23 (20) years or more as of June 30, 2026.
24
Req. No. 3872 Page 4

RBS No. 3872
1 B. Any increase in benefits a person is eligible to receive
2 pursuant to repealed Section 49-136 of Title 11 of the Oklahoma
3 Statutes after June 30, 2020, shall be used to offset the increase
4 in benefits provided in subsection A of this section.
5 SECTION 4. AMENDATORY 62 O.S. 2021, Section 3103, as
6 last amended by Section 2, Chapter 361, O.S.L. 2024 (62 O.S. Supp.
7 2025, Section 3103), is amended to read as follows:
8 Section 3103. As used in the Oklahoma Pension Legislation
9 Actuarial Analysis Act:
10 1. “Amendment” means any amendment, including a substitute
11 bill, made to a retirement bill by any committee of the House of
12 Representatives or Senate, any conference committee of the House or
13 Senate or by the House or Senate;
14 2. “RB number” means that number preceded by the letters “RB”
15 assigned to a retirement bill by the respective staffs of the
16 Oklahoma State Senate and the Oklahoma House of Representatives when
17 the respective staff office prepares a retirement bill for a member
18 of the Legislature;
19 3. “Legislative Actuary” means the firm or entity that enters
20 into a contract with the Legislative Service Bureau pursuant to
21 Section 452.15 of Title 74 of the Oklahoma Statutes to provide the
22 actuarial services and other duties provided for in the Oklahoma
23 Pension Legislation Actuarial Analysis Act;
24
Req. No. 3872 Page 5

RBS No. 3872
1 4. “Nonfiscal amendment” means an amendment to a retirement
2 bill having a fiscal impact, which amendment does not change any
3 factor of an actuarial investigation specified in subsection A of
4 Section 3109 of this title;
5 5. “Nonfiscal retirement bill” means a retirement bill:
6 a. which does not affect the cost or funding factors of a
7 retirement system,
8 b. which affects such factors only in a manner which does
9 not:
10 (1) grant a benefit increase under the retirement
11 system affected by the bill,
12 (2) create an actuarial accrued liability for or
13 increase the actuarial accrued liability of the
14 retirement system affected by the bill, or
15 (3) increase the normal cost of the retirement system
16 affected by the bill,
17 c. which authorizes the purchase by an active member of
18 the retirement system, at the actuarial cost for the
19 purchase as computed pursuant to the statute in effect
20 on the effective date of the measure allowing such
21 purchase, of years of service for purposes of reaching
22 a normal retirement date in the applicable retirement
23 system, but which cannot be used in order to compute
24
